You are comparing:
char *str1 = "Hello";   ❌ risky for modification
char str1[20] = "Hello"; ✔ correct for modification

Let’s explain clearly with memory diagrams and rules.

🧠 1️⃣ What happens in
char *str1 = "Hello";

This does NOT create a string in writable memory.

Instead:
"Hello" is stored in read-only memory (ROM / .rodata section)
str1 only stores the address of that memory

Memory layout
Read-only section:
[ H e l l o \0 ]

Stack:
str1 → address of read-only string
❗ Problem

You cannot modify it:
str1[0] = 'Y';   // ❌ Undefined behaviour

May cause:
segmentation fault
crash

char str1[20] = "Hello";
Here:
compiler creates real array in writable memory
contents copied into array

Memory layout
Stack / RAM:
[ H e l l o \0 _ _ _ _ _ ... ]

str1 → actual array memory
